SCRAPIE, SHEEP- SLOVENIA: OIE
*****************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 5 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information 1 Apr 2005. Vol 18 - No.13 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/ais_77.htm#Sec0>

Scrapie in Slovenia
-----------------
See also: 16 Jul 2004 (Date of previous outbreak of scrapie in Slovenia
reported to the OIE: July 2004).
Immediate notification report
------------------------
Information received on 25 Mar 2005 from Dr Simona Salamon, Deputy Director
General, Veterinary Administration of the Republic of Slovenia, Ljubljana:
Report date: 25 Mar 2005.
Reason for immediate notification: re-occurrence of a listed disease or
infection in a country, zone/compartment following a report declaring the
outbreak ended.
Date of first confirmation of the event: 24 Mar 2005.
Date of start of the event: 9 Mar 2005.
Nature of diagnosis: post-mortem and laboratory.
Details of outbreak:
1st administrative division: municipality of Kocevje
Type of epidemiological unit: farm
Name of the location: Nemska Loka
Date of start of the outbreak: 9 Mar 2005
Species: ovi
Susceptible: 615*
Cases: 1
Deaths: 1
Destroyed --
Slaughtered --
* 399 ewes, 209 lambs and 7 breeding rams
Species: cap
Susceptible: 137**
Cases --
Deaths --
Destroyed --
Slaughtered --
** 94 goats, 40 kids, 3 breeding male goats
Description of affected population: all sheep are crossbred between
Jezersko-solcavska and Texel. In addition to the sheep and goats, there are
also 28 bovines, 5 horses and 6 dogs on the farm.
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Veterinary Institute
Species examined: ovi
Diagnostic tests used: rapid test/Western blot/immunohistochemistry
Date: 9 Mar 2005 / 10 Mar 2005 / 24 Mar 2005
Results: suspicion / positive / positive
The sample was sent to VLA Weybridge, United Kingdom (OIE Reference
Laboratory for scrapie) for discriminatory testing. Source of outbreak or
origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive. Control measures to be
undertaken: partial stamping-out.
